      "commit": {
        "parents": [
          {
            "commit": "7b782ce181865dd8a08b633839c6eabec01fb735",
            "subject": "LU-9119 lnet: fix lnet shutdown race"
          }
        ],
        "author": {
          "name": "Olaf Weber",
          "email": "olaf@sgi.com",
          "date": "2017-01-27 15:13:53.000000000",
          "tz": 60
        },
        "committer": {
          "name": "Amir Shehata",
          "email": "amir.shehata@intel.com",
          "date": "2017-03-03 15:44:14.000000000",
          "tz": -480
        },
        "subject": "LU-9119 socklnd: propagate errors on send failure",
        "message": "LU-9119 socklnd: propagate errors on send failure\n\nWhen an attempt to send a message fails, for example because no\nconnection could be established with the remote address, socklnd\ndrops the message. For a PUT or REPLY message with non-zero\npayload, ksocknal_tx_done() calls lnet_finalize() with -EIO\nas the error code. But for an ACK or GET message there is no\npayload, and lnet_finalize() is called with 0 (no error) as the\nerror code. This leaves upper layers to rely on other means to\ndetermine that sending the message did actually fail, and that\n(for example) no REPLY will ever answer a failed GET.\n\nAdd an error code parameter to ksocknal_tx_done().\n\nIn ksocknal_txlist_done() change the 0/1 'error' indicator to be\nan actual error code that is passed on the ksocknal_tx_done().\nUpdate the callers of ksocknal_txlist_done() to pass in the error\ncode if they have encountered an error.\n\nTest-Parameters: trivial\nSigned-off-by: Olaf Weber <olaf@sgi.com>\nChange-Id: Idf6dc7a3a2c95cecee6b272c35a66ef57a704b52\n"
      },
      "branch": "refs/heads/multi-rail"
    }
  },
  "requirements": [],
